{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617389"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:13:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:13:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16468"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16468"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.41,0,0.41,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9159"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75583"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9159"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16468"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61101"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7659"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"},{"type":"tags","id":"8414"},{"type":"tags","id":"9982"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21745"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21751"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75583"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFollowing restoration of blood flow after cerebral ischaemia, inflammatory mediators and reactive oxygen species are released. Cytokines cause vasoconstriction while reactive oxygen species increase vascular permeability, leading to oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the direct consequence of vasoconstriction and oedema in cerebral reperfusion injury that leads to neuronal damage and glial reactivity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Leukocyte infiltration","Oxidative stress mitochondrial dysfunction","Endothelial dysfunction","Decreased microvascular perfusion","Cytokine release"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn cerebral reperfusion injury, \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased microvascular perfusion\u003C/strong\u003E is the direct result of both vasoconstriction and oedema. This reduction in blood flow leads to neuronal damage and triggers reactive changes in glial cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options represent different aspects of reperfusion injury but are not the direct consequence of vasoconstriction and oedema:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeukocyte infiltration\u003C/strong\u003E is a consequence of endothelial activation and inflammatory signaling\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxidative stress mitochondrial dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by free radical generation during reperfusion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndothelial dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E is an early event that contributes to vasoconstriction and oedema\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytokine release\u003C/strong\u003E is a trigger for vasoconstriction, not its consequence\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of vasoconstriction and oedema physically compromises blood flow through small vessels, creating secondary ischaemic injury that damages neurons and activates glial cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cerebral reperfusion injury involves both vasoconstriction and oedema which reduce blood flow to brain tissue.","Decreased microvascular perfusion leads to neuronal damage and reactive gliosis.","Cytokines and reactive oxygen species contribute to vascular dysfunction in reperfusion injury."],"references":["Attwell D, Buchan AM, Charpak S, Lauritzen M, Macvicar BA, Newman EA. Glial and neuronal control of brain blood flow. Nature. 2010 Nov 11;468(7321):232-43. doi: 10.1038/nature09613. PMID: 21068832; PMCID: PMC3206737.","Metea MR, Newman EA. Glial cells dilate and constrict blood vessels: a mechanism of neurovascular coupling. J Neurosci. 2006 Mar 15;26(11):2862-70. doi: 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4048-05.2006. PMID: 16540563; PMCID: PMC2270788.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61101"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16468"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61101"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T11:45:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T11:45:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9159"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75583"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"cr